    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-11-13T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-11-13T03:00:00-05:00" n="516"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d516">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">683.84A/11–1352: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 516<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Israel (<persName corresp="#p_DMB1"
                            type="from">Davis</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d516fn1">Repeated to Damascus, Paris, Amman, Baghdad,
                        Beirut, Cairo, London, and Rome; sent by pouch to Ankara and Jidda.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tel Aviv</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-11-13T10:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 13, 1952—10 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>779. Re Damascus <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 345 to Dept.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d516fn2">
                        <ref target="#d509">Document 509</ref>.</note> It is believed crux of
                    difficulty is summed up in Damascus <gloss target="#t_desp1">desp</gloss>
                        185<note n="3" xml:id="d516fn3">
                        <ref target="#d494">Document 494</ref>.</note> in statement to effect
                    Colonel Shishikli wishes <hi rend="italic">modus vivendi</hi> (rather than a
                    permanent settlement) that will last “only until such time as Arab rights can be
                    effectively reasserted.” Israel on other hand wants econ and polit as well as
                    mil peace which will permit it to become integrated in the life of the <gloss
                        target="#t_ME1">ME</gloss>. Unless Israel can convince the Arabs that they
                    have much to gain from peace, there wld seem little immediate chance for real
                    progress toward area stability and defense.</p>
                <p>Israel is interested in a durable frontier and might be ready to eliminate the
                    demilitarized zone as the price for peace and friendship, but for a closed
                    frontier, no peace and a continuation of the blockade the proposal outlined in
                        <gloss target="#t_reftel1">reftel</gloss> will have little appeal to the
                    Israelis. Thus Emb believes that however slight the chances of success may be we
                    shld continue to encourage both parties to negotiate directly with each other in
                    the hope that a basis for some progress toward settlement will be found. <gloss
                        target="#t_IG1">IG</gloss> has now expressed willingness discuss problem
                    with Syria, which was not the case a year ago when the <gloss
                        target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> thought no good purpose wld be served. A
                        <hi rend="italic">modus vivendi</hi> certainly cld precede a more formal
                    settlement, <pb facs="1094" n="1054" xml:id="pg_1054"/> but to be mutually satis
                    and produce good results it wld have to be in truth a step toward peace.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DMB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
